Problem Statement 
Create a voice assistant in Python using speech_recognition, pyttsx3, pywhatkit, wikipedia & 
pyjokes. It listens continuously for "Alexa" wake word, recognizes commands via Google API, 
and responds with female voice. Features: play YouTube songs, tell time, search Wikipedia 
("who is..."), tell jokes, funny replies to dating/single questions, and asks to repeat unclear 
commands. Must handle errors gracefully. 
Scope of the Project 
A simple voice assistant (Alexa-like) in Python that: 
● Listens for the wake word "Alexa" 
● Recognizes speech using Google API (needs internet) 
● Speaks back with a female voice (pyttsx3) 
● Can do: 
○ Play songs on YouTube (play shape of you) 
○ Tell current time 
○ Search Wikipedia (who is Elon Musk) 
○ Tell programmer jokes 
○ Give funny replies to "date" or "are you single" 
● Runs in an infinite loop 
Limitations: 
Needs wake word every time, no offline mode, very few commands, no stop command. 
Perfect base for a custom JARVIS-style assistant — easy to expand!  
Functional Requirement 
1. Listen continuously for voice input 
2. Activate only when wake word "Alexa" is spoken 
3. Convert speech to text using Google Speech Recognition 
4. Understand and execute these commands: 
● Play [song name] → Play on YouTube 
● What is the time → Tell current time 
● Who is [person] → Read Wikipedia summary 
● Tell me a joke → Tell a programmer joke 
● Are you single / Date → Give funny response 
5. Speak responses using text-to-speech (female voice) 
6. Print user command and assistant reply in console 
Non Functional Requirement 
1. Must respond within 3 seconds 
2. Requires active internet (Google Speech API) 
3. Works on Windows/Linux/macOS with Python 3 
4. Uses female voice by default 
5. Runs continuously until manually stopped 
6.Handles microphone/network errors gracefully 
7.No data stored (zero privacy risk) 
8.Single-user, single-device only 
9. Lightweight (~50 MB RAM usage) 
SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE 
Type: Single-threaded, rule-based voice assistant 
Flow: 
Microphone → Google STT (online) → Wake word "Alexa" check → Keyword matching (if-elif) 
→ Action (YouTube/Wiki/Joke/Time) → pyttsx3 TTS (offline) → Speaker + Console 
Core Loop: Infinite while True listening 
Dependencies: Internet (for speech recognition only) 
Deployment: Local Python script 
Simple | Linear | Easily extensible 
DESIGN DIAGRAM 
1. USE CASE DIAGRAM (TEXTUAL) 
2. WORKFLOW / ACTIVITY DIAGRAM (TEXTUAL) 
3. SEQUENCE DIAGRAM (TEXTUAL) 
4. ER DIAGRAM (FILE-BASED—>SIMPLIFIED ENTITY 
DIAGRAM) 
